@{" DOpusToBack      " link DOpusToBack}  @{" ParentList       " link ParentList}  @{" User1, ...       " link User1}@{PAR}
@{" DOpusToFront     " link DOpusToFront}  @{" Patternmatch     " link Patternmatch}  @{" Verify           " link Verify}@{PAR}
@{" Encrypt          " link Encrypt}  @{" Play             " link Play}  @{" Version          " link Version}@{PAR}
@{" ErrorHelp        " link ErrorHelp}  @{" PlayST           " link PlayST}@{PAR}
@{" Execute          " link Execute}  @{" Print            " link Print}@{PAR}
@{" FileInfo         " link FileInfo}  @{" PrintDir         " link PrintDir}@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE ComRefInf "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Command Reference Information@{ub}@{PAR}

This section lists the Directory Opus commands in alphabetical order.
Let's begin with an example of an entry's layout, with its component
parts explained as they occur:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

command  argument  [argument2]@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}

This is the syntax of the command. Elements in square brackets are optional.@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

@{" ARexx Only " link ComRefInf 8} / @{" Internal Only " link ComRefInf}@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}

If one of those buttons follows the syntax description of the command, it means that it is a
command that can only be used either from ARexx (the Amiga's inbuilt intercommunication
language) or for buttons (menus, hotkeys or filetypes).
Otherwise, a command can be used both in a button and as an ARexx command.@{PAR}

Below the syntax (or the "Arexx Only" button), the syntax elements are explained in turn.@{PAR}

If necessary, there will follow notes pertaining to the use of the
particular command.@{PAR}

@{FG highlight}Using DirOpus' commands from ARexx@{FG text}@{PAR}

All Directory Opus commands when called from ARexx respond with two
variables: RC (the error status code) and Result. RC will always be an
integer value indicating the severity of an error, 0 being no error.
Result will indicate success or failure of the command, usually
expressed as an integer value, or it may be data, such as the name of
a file.@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE About "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}About@{ub}@{PAR}

This command displays copyright information and mailing addresses.@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE AddCustEntry "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}AddCustEntry  TEXT [USERDATA] [FGPEN] [BGPEN] [SELECTABLE] [SHOW] [BEFORE]@{ub}@{PAR}

@{" ARexx Only " link ComRefInf 8}@{PAR}


         TEXT  is the text for the entry, and may be up to 256@{PAR}
               characters long. The dimensions of the horizontal@{PAR}
               slider are adjusted automatically to the longest@{PAR}
               entry.@{PAR}

     USERDATA  user data for this entry. This is not displayed but@{PAR}
               can be retrieved, defaults to nothing.@{PAR}

        FGPEN  pen colour to display entry in or -1 for default@{PAR}
               file colour, defaults to -1.@{PAR}

        BGPEN  background colour of entry of -1 for default file@{PAR}
               background colour, defaults to -1.@{PAR}

   SELECTABLE  indicates if entry is selectable (0 = not selectable@{PAR}
               or 1 = selectable), defaults to 1.@{PAR}

         SHOW  boolean to update directory display (0 = do not@{PAR}
               update, 1 = update), defaults to 1.@{PAR}

       BEFORE  ordinal entry number before which to add this entry.@{PAR}
               A 0 adds the entry to the beginning of the list, -1@{PAR}
               adds at the end of the list, defaults to -1.@{PAR}


This is similar to the @{" AddFile " link AddFile} command, but allows for entries of
up to 256 characters. Entries added with this command are completely user-defined.@{PAR}

This command will fail if there are any normal entries already in
the active window, so you should always call @{" Clear Win " link ClearWin} before using it.
By default, entries are not sorted in any way; The most recent entry
will be shown as the last.@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = 0 or 1 to indicate failure or success.@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE AddCustHandler "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}AddCustHandler  PORTNAME [WIN]@{ub}@{PAR}

@{" ARexx Only " link ComRefInf 8}@{PAR}


   PORTNAME  name of handler's message port@{PAR}

        WIN  optional; window to add a custom handler to@{PAR}
             (-1 = current window, 0 = left or 1 = right)@{PAR}
             defaults to -1.@{PAR}


This command will attach an ARexx portname to the current
directory buffer. When you manipulate the buffer's entries, Directory
Opus will pass messages to the specified portname. This command is
only used with buffers created using @{" AddCustEntry " link AddCustEntry}. Currently the only
two actions supported are Double-Click and @{" Click-M-Click " link Glos}. As an
example, this system could be used to create a phonebook system or a
NetWork manager with Directory Opus.@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = name of old handler's message port (if there was one)@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE AddFile "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}AddFile  NAME  SIZE  TYPE  SECONDS  COMMENT  PROTECTION  RESERVED  SHOW@{ub}@{PAR}

@{" ARexx Only " link ComRefInf 8}@{PAR}


         NAME  name of entry@{PAR}

         SIZE  size in bytes of entry@{PAR}

         TYPE  type of entry (-1 = file or 1 = dir)@{PAR}

      SECONDS  datestamp of file, seconds from Jan 1, 1978 (date @{PAR}
               that AmigaDOS considers the beginning of time)@{PAR}

      COMMENT  file comment@{PAR}

   PROTECTION  protection bits in ASCII form. `RW' would mean@{PAR} 
               Readable and Writeable.@{PAR}

     RESERVED  reserved, must be 0 for now@{PAR}

         SHOW  update directory display, boolean@{PAR}


This command adds a file or directory entry to the active directory window.@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = 0 or 1 to indicate failure or success.@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE AddIcon "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}AddIcon  [NAME]@{ub}


   NAME  optional; name of file


This will add icons to all selected files and directories in the
active directory window. Directory Opus automatically senses what sort
of file it is (drawer, project, tool, etc.) and will add the
appropriate icon. Under OS2.0, however, we use the Workbench default
icons. You may specify your own icons in the ConfigOpus if the default
icons are not suitable. You may also specify the Default Tool to be
used for project icons. If the name is not given, it will use the
first available selected item in the current directory window.@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE Alarm "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Alarm@{ub}@{PAR}

This command will sound an alarm on both or either of the sound
channels. You could use this command to warn people that they have
selected a dangerous command. For instance, you could modify the
@{" DELETE " link 1.6.delete} button to read:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

Command   Alarm@{PAR}
Command   Delete@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
