@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE AnsiRead "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}AnsiRead  [NAME]@{ub}@{PAR}


   NAME  optional; name of file@{PAR}


This command operates in exactly the same way as the @{" READ " link Read} command,
except that it displays ANSI control sequences (colours and
typestyles) properly, and also handles tab characters correctly. If
the name is not given it will use the first available selected item in
the current directory window.@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE ARexx "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}ARexx [COMMAND]@{ub}@{PAR}


 COMMAND  optional; command to execute@{PAR}


This allows you to launch an ARexx script or execute a
Directory Opus ARexx command from within Directory Opus. If the
command is not given a requester will open asking the user for one.@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE Assign "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Assign [NAME]@{ub}@{PAR}


   NAME  optional; name to assign@{PAR}

This command allows you to assign a logical device name to the
currently active directory. The C: device is an example of a logical
device; it is not a physical disk itself, but is a directory that has
been assigned the name C:. For example, a simple name as Text: can be
assigned to a long and complicated pathname such as:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

DH0:Projects/Work/1989/April/Bits&Pieces/Text@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}

From then on, whenever you enter Text: into a directory field,
you will go straight to the directory at the end of the assigned path,
instead of having to go through all the sub-directories on the way.
You can use the assignment in any other program as well. Logical
device names always end with a colon.@{PAR}

"Assign" also allows you to cancel a previously assigned logical
device, or reassign a device to another directory. To do this, press
the right mouse button over the S (select) button to activate the
@{" GetDevices " link GetDevices} command. Select the assigned device(s) you wish to change,
and invoke the "Assign" command. A requester will appear, into which you
can type the new pathname to be assigned to each device selected. If you
enter a blank string, that logical device will be removed.@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE Beep "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Beep@{ub}@{PAR}

This command will sound a beep on both or either of the sound
channels. You could use this command to signify that a command has
finished. For instance, you could modify the @{" Diskcopy " link 1.9.2.Disk_Copy} option to read:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

Command   DiskCopy@{PAR}
Command   Beep@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}

This command simply calls the system beep routine.@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
