@NODE Encrypt "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Encrypt  [NAME]  [PASSWORD]@{ub}@{PAR}


       NAME  optional; file name@{PAR}

   PASSWORD  optional; password to use@{PAR}


Have you ever had files that you wanted to encrypt so that only
people who knew the password could understand them?  This command
allows you to do just that. It will encrypt all selected files, using
a password that you enter, with a complex algorithm that most people
will find impossible to work out. The resulting files are not written
over the originals, but are instead written to the destination
directory. They will be the same size as the original files, so you
can ensure you have enough room in the destination directory.@{PAR}

To decrypt a previously encrypted file, you should enter the same
password preceded by a minus sign. For example, to decrypt files you
encrypted with the password FOO, select the files, choose the encrypt
command and enter -FOO as the password.@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE ErrorHelp "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}ErrorHelp  [CODE]@{ub}@{PAR}


   CODE  optional; error code@{PAR}


This command gives you more information about DOS error codes than
is generally available. When you select this option, you are asked for
the DOS error code you want help with. Examples of DOS error codes are
123, 205 and 225. You are then presented with a description of that
error and information pertaining to the possible cause and cure of the
error.@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE Execute "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Execute  [FILENAME]@{ub}@{PAR}


   FILENAME  optional; name of a file to execute as a script file@{PAR}


This command will attempt to execute each selected file in turn or
to execute a specific file as a script file. This has the same effect
as if you had run the script file via IconX, or via the Execute command
from the CLI.@{PAR}

Note: This command will only try to execute files with the S @{" protection bit " link 2.1} set.@{PAR}

ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE FileInfo  "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}FileInfo  NAME  [SEPARATOR]  [WIN]@{ub}@{PAR}

@{" ARexx Only " link ComRefInf 8}@{PAR}


        NAME  name of file to give info for (must be in the active or@{PAR}
              specified window)@{PAR}

   SEPARATOR  optional; character used to separate info@{PAR}

         WIN  optional; window to get file from@{PAR}
              (-1 = current window, 0 = left or 1 = right)@{PAR}
              defaults to -1.@{PAR}


This command returns information on the entry called name (which
must be in the active directory window (or the specified window)). The information returned is
separated by a separator (default separator is space), and consists of
the filename, the size in bytes, the size in block (not used yet), the
file type (less the 0 indicates a file, greater than 0 indicates a
directory), the selected status (boolean), the date (days), the date
(seconds), the comment and the protection bits.@{PAR}

The date is returned as a number of days since January 1st, 1978,
and as the number of seconds since midnight. The @{" protection " link Protect} bits are
returned in the format HSPARWED (with a - character where the bit is
not set).@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = information about the file@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE FinishSection "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}FinishSection@{ub}@{PAR}

@{" Internal Only " link ComRefInf}@{PAR}

The FinishSection command forces any preceding programs
(AmigaDOS, Workbench, Script or ARexx) to executing before carrying on
to the next command. The next command need not be a Directory Opus
command; it is just more likely that it will be.@{PAR}

For instance, to add a @{" Beep " link Beep} to the end of the LHArc list
filetype command, you would change the command list to read:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

AmigaDOS  LHARc  v  {f}@{PAR}
Command   FinishSection@{PAR}
Command   Beep@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE Format "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Format  [DRIVE]  [VERIFY]  [QUICK]  [NOICONS]  [FFS]  [INTER]  [CACHE]@{ub}@{PAR}


     DRIVE  optional; drive to format@{PAR}

    VERIFY  optional; format with verify on@{PAR} 

     QUICK  optional; quick format@{PAR}

   NOICONS  optional; format with no icons@{PAR}

       FFS  optional; format fast file system@{PAR}

     INTER  optional; format in international mode@{PAR}

     CACHE  optional; format in directory caching mode.@{PAR}

                      NOTE: Do not use this option when formatting@{PAR}
                      anything else then floppy disks! It was never@{PAR}
                      meant to be used on hard disks, it is more a@{PAR}
                      nuisance than a benefit on such devices.@{PAR}


This allows you to format a new disk. All new disks need to be
formatted before the computer can write to them.@{PAR}

The Verify flag allows you to turn Verify on or off. If Verify is
turned off, the format process will be much faster, but you will not be
made aware of any errors that occur. If you don't completely trust
your disks, leave Verify on.@{PAR}

The FFS option in Format allows you to format a disk to use the
Fast Filing System of Kickstart 2.0. If you are running a Kickstart
less than 2.0, you will still be able to select this option to format a
disk. However, reading FFs-formatted disks is impossible without 2.0
or greater.@{PAR}

International mode allows file and directory names to include
accented characters. Directory caching mode will decrease the capacity
of your disk but the directory reading speed will be much greater.@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE FormatBG "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}FormatBG@{ub}@{PAR}

This is  same as @{" Format " link Format}, just that it operates in background mode.
This allows you to start up a disk format and still use Directory Opus.@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

