@NODE Iconify "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Iconify@{ub}@{PAR}

This command closes the Directory Opus window and screen, de-
allocates as much memory as possible, and then opens a small window on
the Workbench screen. This is known as iconifying, and allows you to
have Directory Opus constantly available while using the minimum amount
of memory.@{PAR}

To determine the initial position of the iconified window,
especially if you start up Directory Opus in the iconified state, you
should inconify Directory Opus, and position the window as you would
like it to appear. Then re-enter Directory Opus and save the
configuration using @{" SaveConfig " link SaveConfig}.@{PAR}

To re-enter Directory Opus, simply click the left mouse button in
the iconified window, then press the right mouse button. If you wish
to quit Directory Opus without going back into it, just click the Close
button at the far left of the iconified window.@{PAR}

If you have the configuration option Iconify Type set to hidden,
the only way to re-enter Directory Opus is with the hotkeys. These
default to CTRL-SHIFT-ALT (the CTRL key, the left SHIFT key and the
left ALT key held down simultaneously), although this may be changed
in the @{" configuration " link 3.19.4} using @{" Configure " link configure}.@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE IconInfo "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}IconInfo  [NAME]@{ub}@{PAR}


   NAME  optional; name of icon (or file with icon)@{PAR}


This command allows you to modify the characteristics of icons
such as Stack size, Default Tool and Tool Types. It operates in a
similar fashion to the Information option in the Icon menu of 
Workbench.@{PAR}

To use this command you may either select the info files
themselves or the actual files or directories the icons belong to.@{PAR}

A requester will appear when you run this command on a valid icon.
The actual appearance of the requester will vary depending on the type
of icon, but in all cases the actual icon imagery will be displayed.
You click on this image with the left mouse button to display the
alternative imagery (if it exists).@{PAR}

The Remap colours button will swap colours 1 and 2 of the icon
displayed. This can be useful to remap icons designed under OS1.3 for
usage under OS2.0, since OS2.0 swapped the light and dark colours
around.@{PAR}

The information displayed for each icon type is listed below.
Once you have made the desired changes to the icon, the Save button
will save the changes to disk. The Skip and Cancel buttons will exit
without modifying the icon on disk.@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}


@{i}Drawer icon: @{ui}@{PAR}

For a drawer icon you may edit the drawer's protection
bits, comment and tool types. The date of the last modification
of the drawer is also displayed.@{PAR}

@{i}Project icon: @{ui}@{PAR}

For a project icon you may edit the project's stack
size, default tool and tool types. Also displayed are the size of
the project in bytes and blocks, and the last modification date.@{PAR}

@{i}Tool icon: @{ui}@{PAR}

For a tool icon you may edit the tool's protection bits,
stack size, comment and tool types. Also displayed are the size
of the tool in bytes and blocks, and the last modification date.@{PAR}

@{i}Disk icon: @{ui}@{PAR}

For a disk icon you may edit the disk's Default Tool.
Displayed are the total number of blocks, and the number of blocks
used and free. The block size, creation date and disk status are
also displayed.@{PAR}

@{i}Trashcan icon: @{ui}@{PAR}

For a trashcan icon the only information available is
the last modification date.@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}


Protection bits (where appropriate) are modified in the same way
as with the @{" Protect " link Protect} command, except that the Hidden and Pure bits are
not accessible.@{PAR}

Tool types (where appropriate) are modified in the same way as
from Workbench. To edit an existing Tool type, simply select it, and
press return when you have modified it. To create a new Tool type,
select the New button. To delete an existing Tool type, select it and
then select the Delete button.@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
