@NODE Modify "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Modify NAME VALUE@{ub}@{PAR}


    NAME  name of item to modify@{PAR}

   VALUE  new value@{PAR}


This command allows you to make quick changes in certain
configuration options from the buttons or menus, rather than going
through the configuration program.@{PAR}

The Modify command requires at least two parameters, the name of the
option to change, and the new value(s) for it. Most values are actually
a combination of flag bits; to determine the desired value, you simply
add the values of the flag bits together.@{PAR}

You can also add and subtract bits. To do this, specify each bit
(or combination of bits) that you wish to add or subtract, preceded by
the appropriate sign (+ for add and - for subtract).@{PAR}

The options you can change are:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}


BankNumber  NUM@{PAR}

    Allows you to specify the bank being shown.@{PAR}


ButtonRows  ROWS@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Buttons/Button rows menu.@{PAR}


CopyFlags  FLAGS@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Operation/@{" Copy " link Copy}@{PAR}

     FLAGS...@{PAR}

          1 = Keep original datestamp@{PAR}

          2 = Keep original protection bits@{PAR}

          4 = Keep original comment@{PAR}

          8 = Set archive bit@{PAR}

         16 = Check destination free space.@{PAR}


DateFormat  FLAGS@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Operation/Date format@{PAR}

     FLAGS...@{PAR}

          1 = AmigaDOS format (DD-MMM-YY)@{PAR}

          2 = International format (YY-MM-DD)@{PAR}

          4 = USA format (MM-DD-YY)@{PAR}

          8 = English/Australian format (DD-MM-YY)@{PAR}

         16 = Name substitution (Today, Tomorrow, etc.)@{PAR}

         32 = 12 hour clock@{PAR}


DefaultTool  TOOLNAME@{PAR}

    The current Default Tool for project icons created with@{PAR}
    @{" AddIcon " link AddIcon}.@{PAR}


DeleteFlags  FLAGS@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Operation/@{" Delete " link Delete}@{PAR}

     FLAGS...@{PAR}

          1 = Ask before commencing delete@{PAR}

          2 = Ask before deleting files@{PAR}

          4 = Ask before deleting non-empty directories@{PAR}

          8 = Set delete protection bit@{PAR}


DirFlags  FLAGS@{PAR}

    Corresponds to System/Directories.@{PAR}

     FLAGS...@{PAR}

          1 = Always move to empty buffer@{PAR}

          2 = Use ExAll() to read directories@{PAR}

          4 = Auto diskchange@{PAR}

          8 = Auto disk load@{PAR}

         16 = Search buffers on Double-click@{PAR}

         32 = Re-read changed or incomplete buffers@{PAR}

         64 = Search buffers on Parent/Root operation@{PAR}

        128 = Expand pathnames@{PAR}


DisplayLength  WIN  TYPE  LENGTH@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Operation/List format's length fields. This@{PAR}
    sets the lengths of some of the directory list items.@{PAR}

        WIN  The window to act upon@{PAR}
             (-1 = current  window, 0=left or 1= right).@{PAR}

     TYPE...@{PAR}

          0 = Name@{PAR}

          1 = Comment@{PAR}

          2 = Filetype@{PAR}


ErrorFlags  FLAGS@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Operation/Error check@{PAR}

     FLAGS...@{PAR}

          1 = Enable DOS requesters@{PAR}

          2 = Enable error requester@{PAR}


FadeDelay  TIME@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Configuration: System/View & Play's fade delay.@{PAR}


Filter Adjust  [FILEPATTERN]@{PAR}

    The global filename filter. If filepattern is not given@{PAR}
    then global filter will be turned off.@{PAR}


Font  IDNUMBER  FONT  SIZE@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Screen/Fonts. This takes three values; the ID@{PAR}
    number of the font to change, the name of the new font, and the@{PAR}
    point size of the font.@{PAR}


     IDNUMBER...@{PAR}

          0 = General (8 point font)@{PAR}

          1 = Directory window font@{PAR}

          2 = Text viewer font@{PAR}

          3 = Buttons@{PAR}

          4 = Menus@{PAR}

          5 = Status bar@{PAR}

          6 = Disk names@{PAR}

          7 = Clock bar@{PAR}

          8 = Requesters@{PAR}

          9 = Path fields@{PAR}

         10 = Button iconify@{PAR}


GeneralFlags  FLAGS@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Operation/General@{PAR}

     FLAGS...@{PAR}

          2 = Display info@{PAR}

          8 = File double-click@{PAR}

         64 = Window slider activate@{PAR}

        128 = Click-m-click drag@{PAR}


HelpFile  PATHNAME@{PAR}

    Allows you to specify a help file to load when @{" Help " link 1.8.?} is@{PAR}
    pressed.@{PAR}


HidePattern PATTERN@{PAR}

    Corresponds to System/Show pattern's hide pattern@{PAR}


IconFlags  FLAGS@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Operation/Icons@{PAR}

     FLAGS...@{PAR}

          1 = Create icons with directories @{PAR}

          2 = Perform all actions on icons as well@{PAR}

          4 = Select icons automatically@{PAR}


IconifyFlags  FLAGS@{PAR}

    Corresponds to System/Clocks.@{PAR}

     FLAGS...@{PAR}

          1 = Memory monitor@{PAR}

          2 = CPU monitor@{PAR}

          4 = Date@{PAR}

          8 = Time @{PAR}

         16 = No window@{PAR}

         32 = Appicon@{PAR}

         64 = Memory in bytes@{PAR}

        128 = C: and F:@{PAR}

    Note that No window and AppIcon are mutually exclusive. If@{PAR}
    the two flags are specified together the results will be@{PAR}
    unpredictable.@{PAR}


ListFormat  WIN  ITEMS@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Operation/List format. The value for this@{PAR}
    is not a combination of flags, but instead a list of numbers@{PAR}
    representing items.@{PAR}

        WIN  The window to act upon@{PAR}
             (-1 = current window, 0=left or 1=right).@{PAR}

      ITEMS  Up to five numbers, which indicate what data is to be@{PAR} 
             displayed and in what order.@{PAR}

     ITEMS...@{PAR}

          0 = Name@{PAR}

          1 = Size@{PAR}

          2 = Protection@{PAR}

          3 = Datestamp@{PAR}

          4 = Comment@{PAR}

          5 = Filetype@{PAR}


OutputCmd  SHELLCOMMAND@{PAR}

    Corresponds to System/AmigaDOS/Shell command. This parameter does@{PAR}
    not work at the moment. Will be corrected in future versions.@{PAR}


OutputWindow  CONSOLEDEFINITION@{PAR}

    Corresponds to System/AmigaDOS/Output window. This parameter does@{PAR}
    not work at the moment. Will be corrected in future versions.@{PAR}


ReplaceFlags  FLAGS@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Operation/@{" Copy " link Copy}@{PAR}

     FLAGS...@{PAR}

          1 = Always replace files@{PAR}

          2 = Never replace files@{PAR}

          4 = Replace only older files@{PAR}

          8 = Ask before replacing@{PAR}


ScreenMode  MODE@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Screen/Screen mode.@{PAR}

     MODE values...@{PAR}

          1 = Open on Workbench's screen@{PAR}

          2 = Open a clone of Workbench's screen@{PAR}

    Mode ID's are also supported. Some common mode ID's@{PAR}
    are...@{PAR}

        32768 = High Res screen@{PAR}

        32772 = High Res Laced screen@{PAR}

        32800 = Super-High Res screen@{PAR}

        32804 = Super-high Res Laced screen@{PAR}

       233508 = Productivity screen@{PAR}

       233509 = Productivity Laced screen@{PAR}

       266240 = A2024 10 Hz screen@{PAR}

       299008 = A2024 15 Hz screen@{PAR}


ScrDepth  DEPTH@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Screen/Screen mode's depth. The depth can be@{PAR}
    2,3, or 4 bitplanes. That is the same as four, eight or sixteen@{PAR}
    colours.@{PAR}


ScreenFlags  FLAGS@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Screen/Screen mode.@{PAR}

     FLAGS...@{PAR}

          1 = Use default screen width@{PAR}

          2 = Use default screen height@{PAR}

          4 = Half-height screen@{PAR}


ScrClockFlags  FLAGS@{PAR}

    Corresponds to System/Clocks.@{PAR}

     FLAGS...@{PAR}

          1 = Memory monitor@{PAR}

          2 = CPU monitor@{PAR}

          4 = date@{PAR}

          8 = Time@{PAR}

         64 = Memory in bytes@{PAR}

        128 = C: and F:@{PAR}


ScrH  HEIGHT@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Screen/Screen mode's height.@{PAR}


ScrW  WIDTH@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Screen/Screen mode's width.@{PAR}


SeparateMethod  WIN  METHOD@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Operation/List format's cycle button.@{PAR}

        WIN  The window to act upon (-1 = current window, 0=left or@{PAR}
             1 = right).@{PAR}

     METHODS...@{PAR}

          0 = Mix files and directories@{PAR}

          1 = Display directories first@{PAR}

          2 = Display files first@{PAR}


ShowDelay  DELAY@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Configuration: System/View & Play's show delay.@{PAR}


ShowFreeFlags FLAGS@{PAR}

    Corresponds to System/Directory flags.@{PAR}

     FLAGS...@{PAR}

          1 = Bytes free@{PAR}

          2 = Kilo/Megabytes free@{PAR}

          4 = Blocks free@{PAR}

          8 = Percentage of space free@{PAR}

    These bits are mutually exclusive. If more than one is@{PAR}
    specified at a time the results will be unpredictable.@{PAR}


ShowPatBits  FLAGS@{PAR}

    Corresponds to System/Show pattern's hidden bit flag@{PAR}

     FLAGS...@{PAR}

          1 = Hide files with hidden bit set.@{PAR}


ShowPattern  PATTERN@{PAR}

    Corresponds to System/Show pattern's show pattern@{PAR}


SortFlags  FLAGS@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Operation/List format's sort flag@{PAR}

     FLAGS...@{PAR}

          1 = Reverse sort in left window@{PAR}

          2 = Reverse sort in right window@{PAR}


SortMethod  WIN  ITEM@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Operation/List format's checked sort item.@{PAR}

        WIN  The window to act upon (-1 = current window, 0=left or@{PAR}
             1 = right).@{PAR}

     ITEMS...@{PAR}

          0 = Name@{PAR}

          1 = Size@{PAR}

          2 = Protection@{PAR}

          3 = Datestamp@{PAR}

          4 = Comment@{PAR}

          5 = Filetype@{PAR}


UpdateFlags  FLAGS@{PAR}

    Corresponds to Operation/Update@{PAR}

     FLAGS...@{PAR}

          1 = Update free disk space@{PAR}

          2 = Scroll directory window to follow operations@{PAR}

          4 = Redraw more than a quarter of a page@{PAR}

          8 = Directory refresh using StartNotify()@{PAR}

         16 = Left-justify filename in status bar@{PAR}

         32 = Display progress indicator@{PAR}

         64 = Current file progress indicator@{PAR}

        128 = Update listview slider while scanning@{PAR}


ViewPlayFlags  FLAGS@{PAR}

    Corresponds to System/View & Play.@{PAR}

     FLAGS...@{PAR}

          1 = Black background between pictures@{PAR}

          2 = Turn audio filter off for 8SVX play@{PAR}

          4 = 8-bits per gun colour@{PAR}

          8 = LoopPlay 8SVX sound files on double-click@{PAR}

         16 = Text viewer borders@{PAR}

         32 = Start animations paused@{PAR}

         64 = Pick best screen-mode@{PAR}

        128 = View in Window@{PAR}


WindowSize  OFFSET@{PAR}

    Adjusts the placement of the center bar of Directory Opus's@{PAR}
    directory windows.@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}


Any Modify command that change display characteristics (screen
size, mode and depth, list format, etc) will not take effect until you
execute the @{" Redraw " link Redraw} command. For commands that only change directory
display characteristics, you use the @{" DisplayDir " link DisplayDir} command to update the
directory display. Some modifications (like date format, hide and show
pattern, etc.) will not take effect until the directory is actually re-
read (for instance, when the @{" Rescan " link Rescan} command is used). For example, 
you could have two buttons configured to switch between a High Res
screen with 8 colours, and a High Res Interlaced screen with 4 colours.
The definitions for these buttons might be:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

LACEON - Command Modify ScreenMode 32772@{PAR}
         Command Modify ScrDepth 2 @{PAR}
         Command Redraw@{PAR}

LACEOFF - Command Modify ScreenMode 32768@{PAR}
          Command Modify ScrDepth 3@{PAR}
          Command Redraw@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}

As another example, you might wish to change the left window to be
sorted by Date, but to leave the right window alone. For this, you
would have the command:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

Command Modify SortFlags 0 3@{PAR}
Command Rescan 0@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
