@NODE Search "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Search  [NAME]  [PATTERN]  [UCNLC]  [WILD]  [BYWORD]@{ub}@{PAR}


      NAME  optional; name of file@{PAR}

   PATTERN  optional; text pattern to search for@{PAR}

     UCNLC  optional; uppercase characters does not equal lower@{PAR}
            case characters.@{PAR}

      WILD  optional; pattern contains wildcard characters@{PAR}

    BYWORD  optional; match only whole words@{PAR}


This command allows you to search all selected files for a
specified string, which may contain wildcards and @{" ASCII codes " link 1.6.search}.
If a match is found, you are told which file contains the string, and you
are given the option to enter the text viewer and read the file. If you
opt to do this, a search for the string is automatically initiated once
the file has been read by the text viewer.@{PAR}

If any directories are selected, all the files within those
directories are also searched.@{PAR}

The flags ucnlc, wild and byword are off by default.@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE Select "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Select  [PATTERN]  [ONLYFILE|ONLYDIRS]  [NAME|DATE|PROTECTION]@{ub}@{PAR}


      PATTERN  optional; pattern to select by@{PAR}

    ONLYFILES  optional; select only files, defaults to both files@{PAR}
               and directories.@{PAR}

     ONLYDIRS  optional; select only directories@{PAR}

         NAME  optional; match on name, (default)@{PAR}

         DATE  optional; match on date@{PAR}

   PROTECTION  optional; match on protection bits@{PAR}


When used in name mode (default) this command allows you to select
files and directories in the active directory window using wildcards.
All standard @{" wildcards " link wldcrdpat} are supported.@{PAR}

When used in date mode you can select all files and directories
created or modified on a certain date only. Simply enter that date
(e.g. 28-Mar-90 would select all entries with datestamps set to any
time on the 28th of March, 1990). You can also use word like
Yesterday, Today, Tuesday, etc. If you can also specify a specific
time. Simply enter the time (in the format HH:MM:SS). If you enter a
time, however, the datestamp must match that time exactly for the
entry to be selected. If you enter a time but not a date it will
select files created today that match that time.@{PAR}

You can also select a range of dates. For instance, to select all
entries created or modified between the 18th of April, 1989 and the
22nd of September, 1991, you would enter:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

18-Apr-89 > 22-Sep-91@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}

The > character does not in this case signify "greater than"; it
simply indicates a range of dates. It must have at least one space on
either side of it.@{PAR}

To select all files from the beginning of time to, for instance,
the 3rd of January, 1990, you would enter:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

> 3-Jan-91
@{LINDENT 1}

To select all files from, for example, the 12th of July, 1983 to
the current date (today) you would enter:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

12-Jul-83 >@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}

You may also specify times when entering date ranges.@{PAR}

If used in protect bit mode you may specify protection bits that
are allowed to be set, and bits that are not. If a bit or group of
bits is allowed to be set, precede it with a + character. If a bit or
group of bits is not allowed to be set precede it with a - character.
The initial + character is assumed. For instance, to select all
readable and writeable files, you would simply enter:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

rw@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}

Or, you could enter:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

+rw@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}

Both these would have the same effect. To expand upon this, and
select all readable and writeable files, but not those that have the
hidden or archive bits set, you would enter:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

rw-ha@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}

Or, to select files that do not have the bits SPED set, you would
enter:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

-sped@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}

The Select command is additive; i.e. entries not matching the
given pattern are not deselected.@{PAR}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = undefined@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
