@NODE Status "Tech Guide/Commands"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Status  VALUE  [SET NEWVALUE]@{ub}@{PAR}

@{" ARexx Only " link ComRefInf 8}@{PAR}


          VALUE  indicates the type of status you want@{PAR}

   SET NEWVALUE  optional; set the status to the specified value@{PAR}


This command returns the value for the specified status command
(listed below). If the set keyword is specified, this command will set
the status to the specified value (if appropriate for that status
command). Most status values can be set.@{PAR}

Some status commands require a sub-number. An example of this is
status 4, which returns the total number of files in a specific
directory window. The directory window may be either 0 (for the left-
hand window), 1 (for the right-hand window) or -1 (for the active
window). The command would therefore be status 4 0 for the left-hand
window, and status 4 1 for the right-hand window.@{PAR}

Status values are as follows:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 3}


 1 - Current directory@{PAR}

      This returns or sets the pathname of the current directory.@{PAR}

      Status 1 [SET PATH]@{PAR}


 2 - Version@{PAR}

      This returns the current version number (as a string).@{PAR}

      Status 2@{PAR}


 3 - Active window@{PAR}

      This returns or sets the active directory window@{PAR}
      (either 0 or 1).@{PAR}

      Status 3 [SET WIN]@{PAR}


 4 - Number of files@{PAR}

      This returns the total number of files in the directory@{PAR}
      window.@{PAR}

      Status 4 WIN@{PAR}


 5 - Number of dirs@{PAR}

      This returns the total number of entries in the directory@{PAR}
      window.@{PAR}

      Status 5 WIN@{PAR}


 6 - Number of entries@{PAR}

      This returns the total number of entries in the directory@{PAR}
      window.@{PAR}

      Status 6 WIN@{PAR}


 7 - Number of selected files@{PAR}

      This returns the total number of selected files in directory@{PAR}
      window.@{PAR}

      Status 7 WIN@{PAR}


 8 - Number of selected dirs@{PAR}

      This returns the total number of selected directories in the@{PAR}
      directory window.@{PAR}

      Status 8 WIN@{PAR}


 9 - Number of selected entries@{PAR}

      This returns the total number of selected entries in the@{PAR}
      directory window.@{PAR}

      Status 9 WIN@{PAR}


10 - Total bytes@{PAR}

      This returns the total number of bytes (sum of the lengths@{PAR}
      of all files) in the directory window.@{PAR}

      Status 10 WIN@{PAR}


11 - Total selected bytes@{PAR}

      This returns the total number of selected bytes (sum of the@{PAR}
      lengths of all selected files) in the directory window.@{PAR}

      Status 11 WIN@{PAR}


12 - Select pattern@{PAR}

      This returns or sets the current Select pattern (used in@{PAR}
      the @{" Select " link Select} command).@{PAR}

      Status 12 [TYPE] [SET PATTERN]@{PAR}

      TYPES...@{PAR}
         0 = Name, Default@{PAR}
         1 = Date@{PAR}
         2 = Bits@{PAR}


13 - Directory name@{PAR}

      This returns the name of the directory that is open in the@{PAR}
      specified window. Setting this to another pathname will read@{PAR}
      that directory.@{PAR}

      Status 13 WIN [SET PATH]@{PAR}


14 - Disk name@{PAR}

      This returns the name of the disk that is open in the@{PAR}
      directory window. This cannot be set (use the @{" Relabel " link Relabel}@{PAR}
      command to change the disk name).@{PAR}

      Status 14 WIN@{PAR}


15 - Disk free bytes@{PAR}

      This returns the number of bytes free on the disk open in@{PAR}
      the directory window.@{PAR}

      Status 15 WIN@{PAR}


16 - Disk total bytes@{PAR}

      This returns the total number of bytes (free+used) on the@{PAR}
      disk open in the directory window.@{PAR}

      Status 16 WIN@{PAR}


17 - Buffered directory name@{PAR}

      This returns the pathname of the directory that is stored in@{PAR}
      a specific directory buffer (from 0 to 255).@{PAR}

      Status 17 WIN BUF@{PAR}


18 - Buffered diskname@{PAR}

      This returns the diskname of the directory stored in a@{PAR}
      specific directory buffer (from 0 to 255).@{PAR}

      Status 18 WIN BUF@{PAR}


19 - Buffered disk free bytes@{PAR}

      This returns the free space on the disk whose directory is@{PAR}
      stored in a specific directory buffer (from 0 to 255). This@{PAR}
      data may no longer reflect the actual free space on that@{PAR}
      disk.@{PAR}

      Status 19 WIN BUF@{PAR}


20 - Buffered disk total bytes@{PAR}

      This returns the total number of bytes (free+used) on the disk@{PAR}
      whose directory is stored in a specific directory buffer@{PAR}
      (from 0 to 255).@{PAR}

      Status 20 WIN BUF@{PAR}


21 - Buffer displayed@{PAR}

      This returns the number of the buffer that is displayed in@{PAR}
      the directory window, a number from 0 to 255. If this is@{PAR}
      set to a specific buffer that buffer will be the one shown@{PAR}
      in the directory window.@{PAR}

      Status 21 WIN [SET BUF]@{PAR}


22 - (unused in Directory Opus 4.x)@{PAR}


23 - (unused in Directory Opus 4.x)@{PAR}


24 - Entries per page@{PAR}

      This returns the number of entries that can be displayed per@{PAR}
      page.@{PAR}

      Status 24@{PAR}


25 - Configuration changed@{PAR}

      This returns a boolean value to indicate whether the @{PAR}
      configuration has been changed since it was last saved.@{PAR}
      See also @{" Configure " link Configure} and @{" SaveConfig " link SaveConfig}@{PAR}

      Status 25 [SET STATE]@{PAR}


26 - Okay string@{PAR}

      This returns the name of the Okay string in requesters.@{PAR}
      This also allows you to select the text of the positive@{PAR}
      button for the @{" Verify " link Verify} and @{" GetString " link GetString} commands.@{PAR}

      Status 26 [SET STRING]@{PAR}


27 - Cancel string@{PAR}

      This returns the name of the Cancel string in requesters.@{PAR}
      This also allows you to select the text of the negative@{PAR}
      button for the @{" Verify " link Verify} and @{" GetString " link GetString} commands.@{PAR}

      Status 27 [SET STRING]@{PAR}


28 - Currently iconified@{PAR}

      This returns a value indicating whether Directory Opus is@{PAR}
      currently iconified and if so what type of iconification it@{PAR}
      is. This will return 0 if not iconified, 1 if iconified and@{PAR}
      2 if button iconified.@{PAR}

      Status 28@{PAR}


29 - (unused in Directory Opus 4.x)@{PAR}


30 - Top text justification@{PAR}

      This returns a value indicating how the text in the status@{PAR}
      bar is rendered.@{PAR}

      Status 30 [SET TYPE]@{PAR}

      TYPES...@{PAR}
         0 = left@{PAR}
         1 = right@{PAR}
         2 = center@{PAR}


31 - (unused in Directory Opus 4.x)@{PAR}


32 - (unused in Directory Opus 4.x)@{PAR}


33 - (unused in Directory Opus 4.x)@{PAR}


34 - (unused in Directory Opus 4.x)@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}


ARexx Results:@{PAR}

@{" RC " link ComRefInf 24} = 0@{PAR}

@{" Result " link ComRefInf 24} = depends on which status was requested)@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
