@NODE SimArgFun "Tech Guide/Simple Argument Functions"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Argument Functions@{ub}@{PAR}

These are the argument functions that can be used as arguments when calling
external programs.@{PAR}

You can use more complicated functions too, to bring up a requester, asking
the user to enter some text or to select a file. Have a look at
the @{" requester functions " link ReqFun} for further information.@{PAR}


{d}  Destination directory window's path@{PAR}

     This will insert the path of the destination directory window.@{PAR}


{f}  First selected entry (with Path)@{PAR}

     Insert the path and filenames of the first selected entry. The@{PAR}
     entry will then be deselected.@{PAR}


{F}  All selected entries (with paths)@{PAR}

     Insert the path and filenames of all selected entries. The@{PAR}
     entries will then be deselected.@{PAR}

     AmigaDOS has limited the length of the command line to 256@{PAR}
     characters. Therefore, if the length of a command line exceeds@{PAR}
     256 characters because of a {F} sequence (or for any reason),@{PAR}
     another command line will be created for the next lot of file@{PAR}
     entries until there are no more selected file entries.@{PAR}


{fu} First selected entry (with path, do not deselect)@{PAR}

     The same as {f} except that the entry is not deselected@{PAR}
     after it is used.@{PAR}

{Fu} All selected entries (with paths, do not deselect)@{PAR}

     The same as {F} except that the entries are not deselected@{PAR}
     after they are used.@{PAR}


{o}  First selected entry (name only)@{PAR}

     The same as {f} except that only the name of the first selected@{PAR}
     entry is used, without the pathname.@{PAR}


{O}  All selected entries (names only)@{PAR}

     The same as {F} except that only the names of the selected entries@{PAR}
     are used, without the pathname. @{PAR}


{ou} First selected entry (name only, do not deselect)@{PAR}

     The same as {o} except that the entry is not deselected after@{PAR}
     it is used.@{PAR}


{Ou} All selected entries (name only, do not deselect)@{PAR}

     The same as {O} except that the entries are not deselected after@{PAR}
     they are used.@{PAR}


{Q}  Query the value of something@{PAR}

     This will query the value of one of DirOpus internal flags and insert@{PAR}
     it. Currently only two values are supported:@{PAR}

        {Qp} - Insert the name of the ARexx port of this invocation of@{PAR}
               Directory Opus. Every Directory Opus running will have a@{PAR}
               unique ARexx port name.@{PAR}

        {Qs} - Insert the name of the public screen Directory Opus is@{PAR}
               using. This can either be something like "DOPUS.1" or@{PAR}
               "DOPUS.2" (the number indicating the invocation count) if@{PAR}
               DirOpus is using its own screen, or "Workbench" if DirOpus@{PAR}
               is running on Workbench's screen.@{PAR}


{s}  Source directory window's path@{PAR}

     This will insert the path of the source directory window.@{PAR}


{v}  Pre-defined variable@{PAR}

     This will insert the content of a variable that was previously defined@{PAR}
     with the @{" SetVar " link SetVar} command. I.e., if you defined a variable "MyVariable",@{PAR}
     you could refer to this variable like this: {vMyVariable}@{PAR}


@ENDNODE
@NODE ReqFun "Tech Guide/Requester Functions"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Requester Functions@{ub}@{PAR}

The Title string is the title that will appear on the requester. You
can just omit the Title string, in which case a default title will be used.@{PAR}

The Default string (preceded by a colon) is the default string that is
to appear in the requester. This too can be omitted.@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}


{RdTitle:Default}   Directory requester@{PAR}

                    Default can be any valid pathname@{PAR}


{RfTitle:Default}   File requester@{PAR}

                    Default can be any valid pathname of filename@{PAR}


{RFTitle:Default}   Multi-select file requester@{PAR}

                    Default can be any valid pathname or filename@{PAR}


{RoTitle:Default}   Font requester@{PAR}

                    Default can be any font name. A point size@{PAR}
                    can be specified with a slash followed by a@{PAR}
                    number (ie. topaz/8)@{PAR}


{RsTitle:Default}   Requester that asks for some text@{PAR} 

                    Default can be any text.@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}


The Default string can contain bracketed letters. These tell Directory
Opus where to insert additional information into the requester. The
supported bracketed letters include...@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}


[o] inserts the last referred filename, only the filename@{PAR}

[f] inserts the last referred filename, both path and filename@{PAR}

[s] inserts the source directory window's path@{PAR}

[d] inserts the destination directory window's path@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}


For example, it would be possible to have your own custom rename button
with the following call function:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

c:rename [f] {RsEnter new filename:Foo.[o]}@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}

In this case a string requester would open with the title "Enter new
filename" and the default of the string field would be "Foo." followed
by the selected filename.@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE WldCrdPat "Tech Guide/Wild Card Patterns"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Wild Card Patterns@{ub}@{PAR}

Directory Opus can use wild cards to make some tasks easier. Wild card
characters are expressions that tell Directory Opus to match (or not
match, in some cases) more than just one character. You may already
have encountered pattern matching in the discussion of the Rename
command.@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}


?  This token will match any single character, but does not@{PAR}
   include none. For example, FI?E would match FILE, FINE and@{PAR}
   FIRE but not FIE.@{PAR}

#  This character tells Directory Opus to match the following@{PAR}
   expression) or more times. For instance, FRE#D would match@{PAR}
   FRE, FRED, FREDD, FREDDD, etc. "#?" will match anything, just@{PAR}
   like "*" (see below).@{PAR}

() is in effect an or. (p1|p2|p3) will match on any one of the@{PAR}
   patterns p1, p2, and p3. For instance, (D*G|C*T) would match@{PAR}
   DOG, CAT, DIG, COT, etc. You may include as many patterns@{PAR}
   inside the parentheses as you like, separated by vertical bars@{PAR}
   (|).@{PAR}

|  Use this token within parentheses to separate different@{PAR}
   expressions you wish to match at the same time. For example,@{PAR}
   "(ab|cd)" will match any one of the items separated by "|"@{PAR}
   (here, "ab" and "cd").@{PAR}

%  Matches 0 characters. This is always (useful in an instance@{PAR}
   like "(foo/bar/%)"). Another example: "CA(M/%)P" will match@{PAR}
   CAMP and CAP.@{PAR}

*  Synonym for "#?", an asterisk will match any number of@{PAR}
   repetitions of any characters, including none. For instance,@{PAR}
   "F*" will match F, FR, FRE, FRED, FREDD, FREDDY, etc.@{PAR}

~  The tilde can be used to negate an expression. Anything that @{PAR}
   would normally match, now will not match. For example,@{PAR}
   "F~(ROFG)" will match FROM but not FROG, "~J*" will not match@{PAR}
   anything starting with J.@{PAR}

[] Brackets enclose a list of characters (a "character class")@{PAR}
   that match any of the characters in the class. "[abc]" tells@{PAR}
   Directory Opus to match either "a", "b", or "c" in this@{PAR}
   position.@{PAR}

~  A tilde at the beginning of a character class matches any@{PAR}
   characters that are not in the class. For example, "[~bc]"@{PAR}
   says "match any character except "b" or "c".@{PAR}

-  A hyphen indicates a character range (only within character@{PAR}
   classes). The expression "[a-z]" represents all the lower case@{PAR}
   letters from "a" to "z".@{PAR}

'  (apostrophe or single quote) Use this character to declare the@{PAR}
   following character to be a literal character, used as it @{PAR}
   stands instead of as a wildcard. This permits you to use the@{PAR}
   characters #, ?, |, %, (,), [,], *, ~ and even an apostrophe as@{PAR}
   themselves rather than as pattern-matching control characters.@{PAR}
   For instance, YEAR*'% will match YEAR1989%, YEAR1990% but not@{PAR}
   YEAR 1989 or YEAR1990 as would normally be the case, with % @{PAR}
   meaning match on nothing. Note that this means that you must@{PAR}
   use '' to match an apostrophe.@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}


Note:  "Expression" in the above table means either a single character
(i.e. "#?"), or an alternation (i.e. "#(ab|cd|ef)"), or a character
class (i.e. "#[a-zA-Z]").@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
