@NODE edfeat "Editing Features"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Editing Features@{ub}@{PAR}

The following editing features can used whenever DirOpus expects you to enter some
text (i.e. in a string requester, or when typing in a directory name at the
@{" directory field" link 1.5.1}.@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}


@{i}Cursor key: @{ui}@{PAR}

Moves the cursor one space in the direction of the arrow.@{PAR}

@{i}Cursor key + Shift: @{ui}@{PAR}

Moves the cursor to the beginning or end of the string.@{PAR}

@{i}Backspace: @{ui}@{PAR}

Deletes the character to the left of the cursor.@{PAR}

@{i}Backspace + Shift: @{ui}@{PAR}

Deletes all chars from the beginning of the string to the current cursorposition.@{PAR}

@{i}Delete: @{ui}@{PAR}

Deletes the character under the cursor.@{PAR}

@{i}Delete + Shift: @{ui}@{PAR}

Deletes all chars from the current cursor position to the end of the string.@{PAR}

@{i}Right Amiga + x key: @{ui}@{PAR}

This is known as Amiga-X; It erases the entire string.@{PAR}

@{i}Right Amiga + c key: @{ui}@{PAR}

This is known as the "Copy to Clipboard" action. It copies the string to the
clipboard. Note: This is only available under AmigaOS 3.5 or higher!@{PAR}

@{i}Right Amiga + v key: @{ui}@{PAR}

This is known as the "Paste from Clipboard" action. It pastes the contents of the
clipboard into the string gadget, starting at the cursor position.This is only
available under AmigaOS 3.5 or higher!@{PAR}

@{i}Right Amiga + q key: @{ui}@{PAR}

This is known as Amiga-Q;  It restores the contents of a field to the previous information.@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE StaExtPrg "Tutorials/Starting External Programs"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}How we start external programs@{ub}@{PAR}

Directory Opus uses the small (4k) AmigaDOS program 'DOpusRT' to help
it launch AmigaDOS, WorkBench, Script and ARexx programs. When you
start up an external program a script file is created in the T:
directory. This script file contains all the initialisation and
execution code needed to start up and manage your programs.@{PAR}

The DOpuRT program is called at the end of the script file, and
communicates with Directory Opus to inform it when the script file has
finished running. This is needed for functions that are not run
asynchronously. It also doubles as a wait command, which is needed for
the adjustable close delay.@{PAR}

To take advantage of the current directory changing, adjustable stack,
and priority you will need the commands CD, Stack and Change TaskPri
in your computer's C:directory. You will also need the commands Run,
Execute, FailAt, NewCLI and EndCLI. These are almost always present
in your C: directory anyway (if not in ROM), so you should not need to
install them.@{PAR}

There are a couple of other points to be aware of. Because external
programs are run via a script file, they can be aborted like any other
script file by pressing CTRL-D. This is only possible if you have an
output window selected. If the script file is aborted in this fashion,
the output window effectively turns into a CLI, so you must type ENDCLI
to remove the window.@{PAR}

The second point is that if the program was not run asynchronously,
Directory Opus will be frozen, waiting for the signal back from the
DOpusRT program. If you abort the script file before it reaches
DOpusRT, Directory Opus will never unfreeze. You can force Directory
Opus to unfreeze by activating the Directory Opus window and pressing
SHIFT-ESC (the shift key in conjunction with the escape key). This also
allows you to turn any non-asynchronous program into an asynchronous
program, while the program is running.@{PAR}

Note that when using NewCLI or NewShell as the Output command, an error
such as unknown command will abort the script file as well. You should
therefore make sure that all your buttons, filetypes, hotkeys or menus
do not try to run nonexistent programs.@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE Glos "Tech Guide/Glossary"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Glossary@{ub}@{PAR}

Some terms used in this manual that you may need to know are:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

@{i}Active (directory window) @{ui}@{PAR}

Denoted by a highlighted disk name. This is the source
directory, the directory that all commands will act upon.@{PAR}

@{i}Buffers (directory) @{ui}@{PAR}

A Directory Buffer is an internal storage area for directory
information. Whenever Directory Opus reads directory
information from a disk, it stores the information in a
Directory Buffer. By storing the directory information in a
buffer, Directory Opus can avoid unnecessarily re-reading the
disk.@{PAR}

@{i}Click-M-Click @{ui}@{PAR}

This is a Directory Opus term. To click-m-click is to click
with the mouse button, move the mouse to another part of the
screen, and press the mouse button again, all with the
double-click time set from Preferences.@{PAR}

This is used for various tasks: @{" swapping " link 1.5.2} the content
of the two directory windows, @{" entering " link 1.5.3.entering} a sub-directory
by displaying it in the destination window and many more.@{PAR}

An alternative to Click-M-Click is Click-Drag-Release (see below).@{PAR}

@{i}Click-Drag-Release @{ui}@{PAR}

This is an alternative method to Click-M-Click (which requires less mouse pointer
gymnastics). Click and hold on an unselected entry. Then, without releasing the
left mouse button, press and release the right mouse button. Still holding the left
mouse button, move the mouse pointer to the other directory window. As you move the
mouse pointer, a copy of the selected entry will follow the mouse. Position the
mouse pointer over the inactive window and release the mouse button.@{PAR}

There's a variation of Click-Drag-Release for the sure handed mouse gymnast: Click
and hold on an unselected entry. Then, without releasing the left mouse button, move
the pointer to the unselected Directory Window and release the mouse button. The
trick to this method is to move the mouse pointer horizontally without moving up or
down.@{PAR}

Click-Drag-Release is only available if the appropriate @{" config setting " link 3.17.5} is
activated.@{PAR}

@{i}Directory Window @{ui}@{PAR}

One of the two windows on the screen in which entries are
displayed.@{PAR}

@{i}Double-click @{ui}@{PAR}

An Amiga term, this means to click twice with the mouse
button (usually the left button, but sometimes the right
button) on an object, within a pre-determined time. The time
is set from within Preferences, and you should consult your
Amiga manual for more information on this.@{PAR}

@{i}Drag'n Drop @{ui}@{PAR}

An Amiga Term. To Drag'n Drop is to click and hold an item with the left mouse button.
Then, without releasing the left mouse button, move the mouse pointer to an other part
of the screen. The item will follow the mouse pointer (you're "dragging" it). Position
the mouse pointer over another item and release the mouse button (now you're "dropping"
the item). DirOpus allowes you to @{" Drag'n Drop Workbench icons " link 1.10} onto its
window or its AppIcon.@{PAR}

@{i}Drive gadgets @{ui}@{PAR}

The 30 gadgets, of which only six are visible at once, that
enable you to easily read any directory.@{PAR}

@{i}Entry @{ui}@{PAR}

Either a file or a directory.@{PAR}

@{i}File types @{ui}@{PAR}

A file type is a set of user-defined tests to see whether a
file is of a certain type or not. Actions can then be
performed on the file, depending on its type.@{PAR}

@{i}Highlight @{ui}@{PAR}

Highlight is the term given to the changing or reversal of
colours, usually when an object is selected.@{PAR}

@{i}Inactive (directory window) @{ui}@{PAR}

Disk name is not highlighted. This is the destination
destination directory, and files may sometimes be written
here from the source directory.@{PAR}

@{i}Menu @{ui}@{PAR}

A pull-down menu is like a list of gadgets. A menu is
accessed by moving the mouse to the top of the screen and
holding the right mouse button.@{PAR}

@{i}Open @{ui}@{PAR}

A directory that currently displayed is said to be open.@{PAR}

@{i}Requester @{ui}@{PAR}

A requester is usually a box that appears on the screen,
soliciting a response. Some requesters require a string
input, others simply ask you to choose yes or no.@{PAR}

@{i}RMB Button @{ui}@{PAR}

A Directory Opus term. This is a button that is selected
with the right mouse button, not with the left mouse button.@{PAR}

@{i}Selected @{ui}@{PAR}

Entries are selected when they are highlighted. This is
usually done by clicking on them with the left mouse button.@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE faq "Frequently asked questions"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Frequently Asked Questions@{ub}@{PAR}

@{FG highlight}1. Why do newer versions of DirOpus refuse to play music modules ?@{FG text}@{PAR}

DirOpus utilizes the inovamusic.library to play various sound/music @{" formats " link 1.6.play}.
This library is Copyright Inovatronics (the former publisher of DirOpus 4). We were not able to
get the rights to that library, as nobody knows the current whereabouts of the original author.@{PAR}

At the time of writing, you can download the Inovamusic.library from
http://www.amclust.de/software/archive/CanDoLibs.lha.@{PAR}

We recommend to use external players anyway, they're much more flexible and support much more
formats. Check Hippoplayer (mus/play/hippoplayer.lha), DeliTracker (mus/play/DeliTracker232.lha)
or EaglePlayer (mus/play/EaglePlayer201.lha, Shareware) for example.@{PAR}

@{FG highlight}2. DirOpus is slooow and my modem makes strange noises when running the program ?!@{FG text}@{PAR}

This only happens with beta releases. This is due to socalled "serial debug output" (the program
sends debugging information to the serial port). If you don't know how to handle this, don't download
beta versions, just stick with the public releases.@{PAR}

Note: Not all beta releases make serial debug output. *Always* read the notes on the homepage and
the "History" file included in the distribution to get informed about problems you might encounter
with a certain release.@{PAR}

If you still want to use beta versions, download "Sushi" or "Sashimi" from Aminet. Make sure
you read and understood the accompanying documentation and run one of those programs before
starting DirOpus.@{PAR}

@{FG highlight}3. But I use a modem to connect to the internet, can I still use beta releases ?@{FG text}@{PAR}

Yes. If you are using Sushi or Sashimi (see previous question), debug output will not
interfere with serial communication between your Amiga and the modem.@{PAR}

@{FG highlight}4. I'm using OS 3.9's XADmaster.library and depacking files will trash filenames !@{FG text}@{PAR}

This is a bug in the version of XADmaster.library distributed on the OS 3.9 CD. Please install
BoingBag 39-1 (available from Amiga Inc.'s homepage). This should cure the problem.@{PAR}

@{FG highlight}5. Support for XADmaster.library does not work !@{FG text}@{PAR}

Make sure the @{" FORCEOPENXAD " link 1.3.1} tooltype is set. If you've got any archive
filetypes defined, make sure their double-click and/or click-m-click actions are undefined.@{PAR}

@{FG highlight}6. When I try to start DOpus from CLI, a requester asks me to insert volume "DOpus:" !?@{FG text}@{PAR}

When starting DOpus from the CLI, you *must* switch to DOpus' directory first. Assuming The
programm can be found in "SYS:Tools/DirOpus", you would have to type the following:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

CD SYS:Tools/DirOpus@{PAR}
DirectoryOpus@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}

If you don't like this, you can either reintroduce the "DOpus:" assign or spread DOpus'
files to various system directories on your boot partition (see next question).@{PAR}

@{FG highlight}7. With previous versions, I had my DOpus files spread around my HD. Is this still possible ?@{FG text}@{PAR}

No problem, as long as you know what you're doing. If DirOpus can't find its files
in its own directory, it will will search them in standard System directories:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

C:      DirectoryOpus, ConfigOpus, DOpusRT, all Modules@{PAR}
S:      Configuration files, helpfiles@{PAR}
LIBS:   Libraries@{PAR}
LOCALE: Catalog files@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}

Just copy the files from the Directory Opus distribution to the appropriate directories
and you can start DirOpus simply by typing 'DirectoryOpus' in the CLI.@{PAR}

@{FG highlight}8. I'd like to continue using the DOpus: Assign. Is this still possible ?@{FG text}@{PAR}

Yes. DirOpus still uses this assign (as a last option, if everything else fails) to find
its files.@{PAR}

@{FG Highlight}9. What is neccessary to start DirOpus when booting without Startup-Sequence ?@{FG text}@{PAR}

If your Computer is equipped with a MC 68060 Processor, you should first start setpatch (simply
type SETPATCH in the CLI), otherwise problems may occur (see next question).@{PAR}

@{FG highlight}10. Why is there no version of DirOpus compiled for a 68060 ?@{FG text}@{PAR}

Compiling the complete Directory Opus Package takes quite much time and there would be no speed
gain for 68060 users. The benefits simply wouldn't justify the efforts. The only drawback is
that SetPatch has to be started before DirOpus on a 68060 equipped Amiga.@{PAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE history "History"
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}History@{ub}@{PAR}

In this section the changes since Directory Opus v4.12 will be monitored.
Only increased functionality will be covered here. For a detailed list of all
the bugfixes and other improvements that were done to the DirOpus source code,
have a look at the History.txt file that accompanies every release of DirOpus.@{PAR}

@{FG highlight}New in Version 4.16:@{FG text}@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

- DOpus can @{" handle archives " link 1.11} now, using @{" XADmaster.library " link reqments}@{PAR}
- New argument @{" -X " link 1.3.2} and tooltype @{" FORCEOPENXAD " link 1.3.1} introduced@{PAR}
- New filetype testing directive @{" MatchI " link 3.12.4.MatchI} introduced@{PAR}
- You can specify a directory as an argument when @{" running DOpus " link 1.3}@{PAR}
- Assigns can be removed using @{" Delete " link 1.6.delete} function on device list entries@{PAR}
- @{" Text Viewer " link 2.7} can open its window on DirOpus' screen now@{PAR}
- File sizes can be displayed in @{" Kilobyte/Megabyte/GigaByte " link 3.17.7.displayed} now@{PAR}
- @{" Sysinfo.library " link reqments} can be used to calculate CPU load@{PAR}
- The AppIcon can be @{" changed " link 3.19.2.icon.an} now@{PAR}
- Updating sliders while reading directory can be @{" turned off " link 3.17.8}@{PAR}
- The assign "DOpus:" is @{" not needed " link installation} anymore@{PAR}
- OS 3.5/3.9 icons are supported now@{PAR}
- DirOpus supports file links now@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}

@{FG highlight}New in Version 4.15:@{FG text}@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

- Powerpacker support replaced by @{" XFDMaster " link reqments} support@{PAR}
- New argument @{" -x " link 1.3.2} and tooltype @{" FORCEOPENXFD " link 1.3.1} introduced@{PAR}
- Increased maximum @{" displayed file name characters " link 3.17.7.displayed} to 64@{PAR}
- 'Bring to front' option added to 'DirOpus already running' requester@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}

@{FG highlight}New in Version 4.14:@{FG text}@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

- @{" PopUp menu " link 1.5.2} added to allow changing the sorting order on the fly@{PAR}
- Additional keystrokes in @{" text viewer " link 2.7}@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}

@{FG highlight}New in Version 4.13:@{FG text}@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

- Long filename support (up to 107 Characters).@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 1}

@ENDNODE
